{
  "text": "In systems theory, reduced order modeling has also been extensively studied under the name of model reduction [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] . Contrary to model reduction where approximation is measured using L 2 norms we are interested in L \u221e norms. The guarantees provided by L \u221e norms are more natural when applications to safety verification are of interest.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "42165470",
    "[CITATION_2]": "7716718"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "42165470": {
      "title": "Model reduction of multidimensional and uncertain systems",
      "abstract": "Model reduction methods are presented for systems represented by a linear fractional transformation on a repeated scalar uncertainty structure. These methods involve a complete generalization of balanced realizations, balanced Gramians, and balanced truncation model reduction with guaranteed error bounds, based on solutions to a pair of linear matrix inequalities which generalize Lyapunov equations. The resulting reduction methods immediately apply to uncertainty simplification and state order reduction in the case of uncertain systems but also may be interpreted as state order reduction for multidimensional systems."
    },
    "7716718": {
      "title": "A survey of model reduction methods for large-scale systems",
      "abstract": "An overview of model reduction methods and a comparison of the resulting algorithms is presented. These approaches are divided into two broad categories, namely SVD based and moment matching based methods. It turns out that the approximation error in the former case behaves better globally in frequency while in the latter case the local behavior is better."
    }
  }
}